04229nam a22006615i 9780823291038DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20222004nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232910387 a10.1515/97808232910382doi  a(DE-B1597)566168  a(OCoLC)1306541782  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0180002bisacsh1 aBigger, Charles P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBetween Chora and the Good :bMetaphor's Metaphysical Neighborhood /cCharles P. Bigger. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (576 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerspectives in Continental Philosophy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1 The Place of Metaphor -- tChapter 2 The Matrix -- tChapter 3 Plato’s Idea Theory -- tChapter 4 To Feel and to Know -- tChapter 5 Deictic Metaphor -- tChapter 6 Truth and Metaphor -- tChapter 7 Aristotle: Poetry and the Proper -- tChapter 8 “To the Things Themselves” -- tChapter 9 The Hypostasis: Its Thisness and Its There -- tChapter 10 Elementals -- tChapter 11 Time’s Arrow -- tChapter 12 The Originary -- tChapter 13 Otherwise than Metaphor -- tChapter 14 Saying Something -- tChapter 15 The Receptacle -- tChapter 16 À Dieu -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPlato's chora as developed in the Timaeus is a creative matrix in which things arise and stand out in response to the lure of the Good. Chora is paired with the Good, its polar opposite; both are "beyond being" and the metaphors hitherto thought to disclose the transcendent. They underlie Plato's distinction of a procreative gap between being and becoming. The chiasmus between the Good and chora makes possible their mutual participation in one another. This gap makes possible both phenomenological and cosmological interpretations of Plato. Metaphor is restricted to beings as they appear in this gap through the crossing of metaphor's terms, terms that dwell with, rather than subulate, one another. Hermeneutically, through its "is" we can see something being engendered or determined by that crossing. Bigger's larger goal is to align the primacy of the Good in Plato and Christian Neoplatonism with the creator God of Genesis and the God of love in the New Testament.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Phenomenology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311118960408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831107072980 cprintz978082322350340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329103840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823291038423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823291038/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-118960-4  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK